XCIII. There are three kinds of mistletoe. One that grows as a parasite on the. fir and the larch is called steljs in Euboea and hyphear in Arcadia, and the name of mistletoe is used for one growing on the oak, hard oak, holm—oak, wild pear, turpentine—tree‚ and indeed most other trees3 and growing in great abundance on the oak is one which they call dryos hyphear. There is a difference in the case of every tree except the holm· oak and the oak in the smell and poison of the berry and the disagreeably scented leaf, both the berry and the leaf of the mistletoe being bitter and sticky. The hyphear is more useful than tare for fattening cattle; at first it only acts as a purge, but it subsequently fattens the beasts that have stood the purging process, although they say that those with some interna] malady cannot stand it. This method of treatment is employed for forty days in summer. An additional variety is said to be found in mistletoe, in that when it grows on deciduous trees it also sheds its leaves itseIf, but when growing on an evergreen tree it retains its leaves. But universally when mistletoc seed is sown it never sprouts at all, and only when passed in the excrement of birds, particularly the pigeon and the thrush: its nature is such that it will not shoot unless it has been ripcned in the stomach of birds.
